Upon realizing this, I asked myself: "Why did I find what happened to her so disgusting, but feel that what happened to the soldiers is pretty much normal except the few she executed extrajudicially?" I think maybe we are desensitized toward violence when it is committed by those who are on top who have control of the system. We are so used to it that we think it's normal. For example, when a violent murderer kills multiple people in a crime, we may feel the murderer deserves a painful death, but when politicians make a decision to throw away tens of thousands of lives in a war they know was unnecessary purely for political influence, we merely speak ill of their character. When a billionaire banker screw up thousands of people's livelihoods, we just thought he was bad and should face trial. But when someone vandalizes a vending machine for a few drinks, we lose our shit and decry the decay of public morals. I think there is value in seeing our own hypocrisy.

Didn't jerk to this but I think it's a little bit thought provoking. Upon finishing this my gut reaction was: Sure she was terrible, but the moral decision would be putting her up for trial or killing her on the spot without all the rape stuff. However, on a second thought, didn't most of the soldiers experience the exact same torture? Assuming the foot-soldiers are conscripts which they often are during world wars, they had no choice in becoming cannon fodders. They had no choice but to obey every order from their superior. They had no choice in living in terrible conditions and eating the worst food rations provided for them. In a sense, they are just like the commander without limbs, in that they have no agency for their life and all they could do is the same as what the commander did while she was raped day by day: "Enduring the terrible torture and hoping that one day they will be able to get out alive".
